om","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: variant of   Gore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gore","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece of land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i>, a derivative of <i>gār</i> ‘spear’, with reference to the triangular shape of a spearhead), a topographic name for someone living by a triangular field, or a habitational name from any of various places, for example Gore Court in Tunstall (Kent) and Gore Farm in Hannington (Wiltshire), named from this word.","French: from Old French <i>gore</i> ‘sow’ (a word of allegedly imitative origin, reflecting the grunting of the animal), applied as a metonymic occupational name for a swineherd or as an unflattering nickname.","French: probably also from a pet form of a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Grégoire</i> (see   Gregory  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":27,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Anne Gare was born in 1428, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, her father, Thomas Gare, was 26 and her mother, Dorothy Savage, was 25. She married John Abbott II in 1450, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1460, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1428–1460":"1428–1460","1435–1490":"1435–1490","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1460–1540":"1460–1540","1402–1452":"1402–1452","1403–1463":"1403–1463","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1452":"1452","1463":"1463","1540":"1540","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1428":"1428","England":"England","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1428–1460":"1428–1460","1435–1490":"1435–1490","1450–1490":"1450–1